\begin_layout Section
Time-convolutionless master equation for mesoscopic electron-phonon systems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
These notes are developed from:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
A.
 Pereverzev, and E.R.
 Bittner, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Time-convolutionless master equation for mesoscopic electron-phonon systems,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 J Chem Phys 
\series bold
125
\series default
, 104906 (2006); doi: 10.1063/1.2348869
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Start with the Hamiltonian for the electronic system coupled to oscillators:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{H}=\sum_{n}\epsilon_{n}\ket{n}\bra{n}+\sum_{nmi}g_{nmi}\ket{n}\bra{m}\left(\hat{a}_{i}^{\dagger}+a_{i}\right)+\sum_{i}\omega_{i}\hat{a}_{i}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{n}$
\end_inset

 are electronic states, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a}_{i}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 are annihilation and creation operators for the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th oscillator
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Divide this into a diagonal part 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}_{0}$
\end_inset

 and an off-diagonal part 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{H}=\hat{H}_{0}+\hat{V}
\]

\end_inset

with
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{H}_{0}=\sum_{n}\epsilon_{n}\ket{n}\bra{n}+\sum_{nni}g_{nni}\ket{n}\bra{n}\left(\hat{a}_{i}^{\dagger}+a_{i}\right)+\sum_{i}\omega_{i}\hat{a}_{i}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{i}
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{V}=\sum_{nmi,n\neq m}g_{nmi}\ket{n}\bra{m}\left(\hat{a}_{i}^{\dagger}+a_{i}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
This is useful because:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Often 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{nmi}$
\end_inset

 are small compared to 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{nni}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}$
\end_inset

 can be treated as a perturbation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Often, an initial density matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\rho}\left(0\right)$
\end_inset

 can be chosen to commute with 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}_{0}$
\end_inset

, resulting in simpler forms of the master equations
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Diaognalization:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Diagonalize 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}_{0}$
\end_inset

 with respect to the normal mode degrees of freedom
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\hat{U} & =\exp\left(-\sum_{ni}\left(\frac{g_{nni}}{\omega_{i}}\right)\ket{n}\bra{n}\left(\hat{a}_{i}^{\dagger}+a_{i}\right)\right)\\
 & =\sum_{n}\ket{n}\bra{n}\exp\left(-\sum_{ni}\left(\frac{g_{nni}}{\omega_{i}}\right)\left(\hat{a}_{i}^{\dagger}+a_{i}\right)\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{H}_{0}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{H}_{0}=\hat{U}^{-1}\hat{H}_{0}\hat{U}=\sum_{n}\tilde{\epsilon}_{n}\ket{n}\bra{n}+\sum_{i}\omega_{i}\hat{a}_{i}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{i}
\]

\end_inset

with renormalized electronic energies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{\epsilon}_{n}=\epsilon_{n}-\sum_{i}\frac{g_{nmi}^{2}}{\omega_{i}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Transform 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{V}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{V}=\hat{U}^{-1}\hat{V}\hat{U}=\sum_{\stackrel{n\neq m}{nmi}}\left(g_{nmi}\ket{n}\bra{m}\left(\hat{a}_{i}^{\dagger}+a_{i}-\frac{2g_{nni}}{\omega_{i}}\right)\exp\left(\sum_{j}\frac{g_{nnj}-g_{mmj}}{\omega_{j}}\left(\hat{a}_{j}^{\dagger}-a_{j}\right)\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
A more compact form for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{V}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{V}=\sum_{\stackrel{n\neq m}{nmi}}\ket{n}\bra{m}\hat{M}_{nmi},
\]

\end_inset

with
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{M}_{nmi}=g_{nmi}\left(\hat{a}_{i}^{\dagger}+a_{i}-\frac{2g_{nni}}{\omega_{i}}\right)\exp\left(\sum_{j}\frac{g_{nnj}-g_{mmj}}{\omega_{j}}\left(\hat{a}_{j}^{\dagger}-a_{j}\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The reorganization energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{nm}^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is the sum
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{nm}^{\lambda}=\sum_{j}\frac{\left(g_{nnj}-g_{mmj}\right)^{2}}{\omega_{j}^{2}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Energy difference between the renormalized energies:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta E_{nm}=\tilde{\epsilon}_{n}-\tilde{\epsilon}_{m}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Initial state 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\rho}\left(0\right)$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Take the initial density matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\rho}\left(0\right)=\ket{n}\bra{n}\frac{\exp\left(-\beta\sum_{i}\omega_{i}\hat{a}_{i}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{i}+\sum_{i}g_{nmi}\left(\hat{a}_{i}^{\dagger}+a_{i}\right)\right)}{\text{Tr}\,\left(\exp\left(-\beta\sum_{i}\omega_{i}\hat{a}_{i}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{i}+\sum_{i}g_{nmi}\left(\hat{a}_{i}^{\dagger}+a_{i}\right)\right)\right)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
This is the electronic system prepared in one state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{n}$
\end_inset

, and the oscillators in displaced equilibrium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The electronic density operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{n}\bra{n}$
\end_inset

 commutes with the unitary operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{U}$
\end_inset

 so that the transformed intial density operator is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{\rho}_{0}=\ket{n}\bra{n}\frac{\exp\left(-\beta\sum_{i}\omega_{i}\hat{a}_{i}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{i}\right)}{\text{Tr}\,\left(\exp\left(-\beta\sum_{i}\omega_{i}\hat{a}_{i}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{i}\right)\right)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsection
Development of a Master Equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Breuer and Petruccione have a projection operator formalism that is used
 tod evelop the master equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let there be projection operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 such that th einitial total density matrix satisfies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\rho}\left(0\right)=\mathcal{P}\hat{\rho}\left(0\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The projection 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\hat{\rho}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 may be shown to solve at least two different master equations:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The Nakajima-Zwanzig (NZ) equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\mathcal{P}\hat{\rho}\left(t\right)}{\partial t}=-\int_{0}^{t}d\tau\mathcal{K}^{\text{NZ}}\left(t-\tau\right)\mathcal{P}\hat{\rho}\left(\tau\right)\label{eq:Nakajima-Zwanzig}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The time-convolutionless (CL) master equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\mathcal{P}\hat{\rho}\left(t\right)}{\partial t}=-\int_{0}^{t}d\tau\mathcal{K}^{\text{CL}}\left(\tau\right)\mathcal{P}\hat{\rho}\left(\tau\right)\label{eq:ConvolutionlessMaster}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Since (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Nakajima-Zwanzig"

\end_inset

) is better known than (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ConvolutionlessMaster"

\end_inset

), we derive (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ConvolutionlessMaster"

\end_inset

) from (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Nakajima-Zwanzig"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Apply the Laplace transform to both sides of (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Nakajima-Zwanzig"

\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s\mathcal{P}\hat{\rho}\left(s\right)-\mathcal{P}\hat{\rho}\left(0\right)=-\mathcal{K}\left(s\right)\mathcal{P}\hat{\rho}\left(s\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}\left(s\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\rho}\left(s\right)$
\end_inset

 are the Laplace transforms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\rho}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

, respectively
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\rho}\left(s\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s+\mathcal{K}\left(s\right)\mathcal{P}\hat{\rho}\left(s\right)=\mathcal{P}\hat{\rho}\left(0\right)
\]

\end_inset

 so that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{P}\hat{\rho}\left(s\right)=\frac{\mathcal{P}\hat{\rho}\left(0\right)}{s+\mathcal{K}\left(s\right)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Take the inversere Laplace transform:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{P}\hat{\rho}\left(t\right)=\mathcal{V}\left(t\right)\mathcal{P}\hat{\rho}\left(0\right)\quad\text{with}\quad\mathcal{V}\left(t\right)=\frac{1}{2\pi i}\int_{\kappa-i\infty}^{\kappa+i\infty}\frac{e^{st}}{s+\mathcal{K}\left(s\right)}ds\label{eq:InverseLaplacian}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary positive constant so taht the contour of integration lies
 to teh right of all signularities in the integrand
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Take the time derivative of (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:InverseLaplacian"

\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\left(\mathcal{P}\hat{\rho}\left(t\right)\right)=\mathcal{F}\left(t\right)\hat{\rho}\left(t\right),
\]

\end_inset

with
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{F}\left(t\right)=\frac{\partial\mathcal{V}\left(t\right)}{\partial t}\mathcal{V}^{-1}\left(t\right)
\]

\end_inset

which may be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{K}^{\text{CL}}\left(\tau\right)=-\frac{\partial\mathcal{F}\left(\tau\right)}{\partial\tau}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
It is impossible to calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}^{\text{NZ}}\left(\tau\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}^{\text{CL}}\left(\tau\right)$
\end_inset

 for most realistic systems
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Use a perturbation expansion for these superoperators
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{K}_{2}^{\text{NZ}}\left(\tau\right)=\mathcal{K}_{2}^{\text{CL}}\left(\tau\right)=\mathcal{P}\mathcal{L}_{V}e^{-i\mathcal{L}_{0}\tau}\mathcal{L}_{V}\mathcal{P}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Terms:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}_{0}\hat{\rho}=\tilde{H}_{0}\hat{\rho}-\hat{\rho}\tilde{H}_{0},\quad\text{and}\quad\mathcal{L}_{V}\hat{\rho}=\tilde{V}\hat{\rho}-\hat{\rho}\tilde{V}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{0}$
\end_inset

 - Liouville superoperstor corresponkding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{H}_{0}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{V}$
\end_inset

 - Liouville superoperstor corresponkding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{V}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The convolutionless approach is time-local and a better approximation to
 the exact solution than the Nakajima-Zwanzig equation
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Use the projection operator that acts on the total density matrix as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{P}\hat{\rho}=\sum_{n}\ket{n}\bra{n}\hat{\rho}_{\text{eq}}^{\text{os}}\text{Tr}\,\left(\ket{n}\bra{n}\hat{\rho}\right),\label{eq:ProjectionOperator}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The trace is taken over both electronic and oscillator degrees of freedom
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The density matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\rho}_{\text{eq}}^{\text{os}}=\frac{e^{-\beta\sum_{i}\omega_{i}\hat{a}_{i}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{i}}}{\text{Tr}\,\left(e^{-\beta\sum_{i}\omega_{i}\hat{a}_{i}^{\dagger}\hat{a}_{i}}\right)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The probability for finding the electronic system in state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{n}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{n}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{n}=\text{Tr}\,\left(\ket{n}\bra{n}\hat{\rho}\right)
\]

\end_inset

so that the projection operator of (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ProjectionOperator"

\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{P}\hat{\rho}=\sum_{n}P_{n}\ket{n}\bra{n}\hat{\rho}_{\text{eq}}^{\text{os}},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Time-convolutionless equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sum_{n} & \frac{dP_{n}\left(t\right)}{dt}\ket{n}\bra{n}\hat{\rho}_{\text{eq}}^{\text{os}}=\\
 & -\sum_{nmij}\prime\ket{n}\bra{n}P_{n}\left(t\right)\times\int_{0}^{t}d\tau\,\text{Tr}\,\left(e^{i\left(\tilde{\epsilon}_{n}-\tilde{\epsilon}_{m}\right)\tau}\hat{M}_{nmi}\hat{M}_{mnj}\left(-\tau\right)\hat{\rho}_{\text{eq}}^{\text{os}}+e^{-i\left(\tilde{\epsilon}_{n}-\tilde{\epsilon}_{m}\right)\tau}\hat{M}_{nmi}\hat{M}_{mnj}\left(\tau\right)\hat{\rho}_{\text{eq}}^{\text{os}}\right)\\
 & +\sum_{nmij}\prime\ket{m}\bra{m}P_{n}\left(t\right)\times\int_{0}^{t}d\tau\,\text{Tr}\,\left(e^{i\left(\tilde{\epsilon}_{n}-\tilde{\epsilon}_{m}\right)\tau}\hat{M}_{nmi}\hat{M}_{mnj}\left(-\tau\right)\hat{\rho}_{\text{eq}}^{\text{os}}+e^{-i\left(\tilde{\epsilon}_{n}-\tilde{\epsilon}_{m}\right)\tau}\hat{M}_{nmi}\hat{M}_{mnj}\left(\tau\right)\hat{\rho}_{\text{eq}}^{\text{os}}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Here,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{M}_{mnj}\left(\tau\right)=e^{i\tilde{H}_{0}\tau}\hat{M}_{nmi}e^{-i\tilde{H}_{0}\tau}
\]

\end_inset

and the primes (
\begin_inset Formula $\prime$
\end_inset

) in the summations indicate that 
\begin_inset Formula $m\neq n$
\end_inset

 is excluded
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Multiply both sides of this expression by 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{n}\bra{n}$
\end_inset

 and take the trace:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dP_{n}}{dt}=\sum_{m}W_{nm}\left(t\right)P_{m}-\sum_{m}W_{nm}\left(t\right)P_{n}\left(t\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{nm}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 are time-dependent rates
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
W_{mn}\left(t\right)=2\mathfrak{Re}\int_{0}^{t}d\tau\sum_{ij}\braket{M_{nmi}M_{mnj}\left(\tau\right)}e^{i\left(\tilde{\epsilon}_{n}-\tilde{\epsilon}_{m}\right)\tau}\label{eq:TimeDependentRate}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 and the correlation functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\braket{M_{nmi}M_{mnj}\left(\tau\right)}$
\end_inset

 are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\braket{M_{nmi}M_{mnj}\left(\tau\right)}=\text{Tr}\,\left(M_{nmi}M_{mnj}\left(\tau\right)\hat{\rho}_{\text{eq}}^{\text{os}}\right)\label{eq:CorrelationFunctions}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The explicit form of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{nmi}$
\end_inset

 can be used to reduce the correlation functions to the averaging of displacemen
t operators over the equilibrium ensemble
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\braket{M_{nmi}M_{mnj}\left(\tau\right)} & =g_{nmi}g_{mnj}\left(\Delta_{nmi}\left(\bar{n}_{i}+1\right)e^{i\omega_{i}\tau}-\Delta_{nmi}\bar{n}_{i}e^{-i\omega_{i}\tau}+\Omega_{nmi}\right)\times\nonumber \\
 & \quad\left(\Delta_{nmj}\left(\bar{n}_{j}+1\right)e^{i\omega_{i}\tau}-\Delta_{nmj}\bar{n}_{j}e^{-i\omega_{i}\tau}+\Omega_{nmj}\right)+\nonumber \\
 & \quad\left(\delta_{ij}\left(\bar{n}_{i}+1\right)e^{i\omega_{i}\tau}+\delta_{ij}\bar{n}_{i}e^{-i\omega_{i}\tau}\right)q_{nm}\left(\tau\right)f_{nm}\left(\tau\right)\label{eq:CorrelationFunctionsReduced}
\end{align}

\end_inset

with
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta_{nmi}=\frac{\left(g_{nni}-g_{mmi}\right)}{\omega_{i}},\quad\Omega_{nmi}=\frac{g_{nni}+g_{mmi}}{\omega_{i}},\quad\bar{n}_{i}=\frac{1}{e^{\beta\omega_{i}-1}},\quad\text{and}\quad q_{nm}\left(\tau\right)=e^{i\sum_{j}\Delta_{nmj}^{2}\sin\omega_{j}\tau}
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{nm}\left(\tau\right)=e^{-2\sum_{j}\left(\bar{n}_{n}+\frac{1}{2}\right)\Delta_{nmj}^{2}\left(1-\cos\omega_{j}\tau\right)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{nni}=0$
\end_inset

, the correlation functions of (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CorrelationFunctionsReduced"

\end_inset

) reduce to those obtained by Fermi's golden rule.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{nni}/\omega_{i}\gg1$
\end_inset

, the golden rule approach is not applicable
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The qualitative behavior of 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{n}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 depends on the explicit form of the time-dependent rates 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{mn}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Simplifications
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
For large systems, expect (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:TimeDependentRate"

\end_inset

) to decay to zero so that 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{mn}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 are constant in the long time limit
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Expressions for 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{mn}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 may be replaced by their time-independent Markovian limits in the long-time
 limit [i.e., if electronic relaxation times are much longer than the decay
 rate of the integrand in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:TimeDependentRate"

\end_inset

]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When a model satisfies the condition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{j}\left(\bar{n}_{j}+\frac{1}{2}\right)\Delta_{nmj}^{2}\gg0
\]

\end_inset

 and with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{nmi}$
\end_inset

 taken as a smooth function of 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, we can approximate 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{nm}\left(\tau\right)$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{nm}\left(\tau\right)\sim e^{a_{nm}\tau^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

with
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{nm}=\sum_{j}\left(\bar{n}_{j}+\frac{1}{2}\right)\Delta_{nmj}^{2}\omega_{j}^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{i}\tau\ll1$
\end_inset

, we use a small angle approximation in 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{mn}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\omega_{i}\tau\sim\omega_{i}\tau$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q_{nm}\left(t\right)\simeq e^{i\gamma_{nm}t}
\]

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma=\sum_{i}\Delta_{nm}^{2}\omega_{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Under these approximations, the long-time (Markovian) limit of 
